## 🔥 The Problem

Urban Heat Islands (UHIs) cause city temperatures to run **2–10°C hotter** than surrounding rural areas. This kills people. During the 2003 European heatwave, 70,000 died — the majority in cities. As climate change intensifies, cities must know *where* it's hottest, *who* is most vulnerable, and *what* interventions (tree planting, cool roofs, parks) will help most.

**HeatWatch** gives city planners, researchers, and communities a free, open tool to map urban heat, identify vulnerable neighborhoods, and model the cooling impact of green infrastructure — no GIS expertise required.

---

## 🎯 Who Is This For?

| User | Use Case |
|------|----------|
| 🏙️ City planners & municipal governments | Prioritize cooling interventions by neighborhood |
| 🎓 Students & researchers | Learn geospatial climate analysis with real data |
| 🌿 NGOs & community orgs | Advocate for cooling resources in vulnerable areas |
| 💻 Software engineers | Contribute to open climate tooling |

---

## ✨ Key Features (MVP)

- **🗺️ Heat Map Generation** — Load Landsat satellite data and generate Land Surface Temperature (LST) maps for any city
- **📊 Neighborhood Risk Scoring** — Overlay census/demographic data to identify the most heat-vulnerable communities
- **🌳 Green Coverage Analysis** — Calculate NDVI (vegetation index) to correlate tree cover with temperature
- **📈 Time-Series Comparison** — Compare heat profiles across years to measure change
- **📤 Export-Ready Outputs** — GeoJSON, PNG, and CSV exports for use in reports and GIS tools

---

## 🖥️ Demo

```
$ heatwatch analyze --city "Chicago, IL" --year 2023 --output ./results

✅ Fetching Landsat 9 data for Chicago, IL (2023-06-01 → 2023-08-31)...
✅ Computing Land Surface Temperature...
✅ Computing NDVI vegetation index...
✅ Scoring 77 community areas for heat vulnerability...

📊 Results:
  Hottest neighborhood:  West Pullman       (avg LST: 42.1°C)
  Coolest neighborhood:  Lincoln Park       (avg LST: 31.8°C)
  Most vulnerable:       Englewood          (LST 40.3°C, low tree cover, elderly population)
  Output saved to:       ./results/chicago_2023/

🗺️  Open results/chicago_2023/heatmap.html in your browser to explore.
```

> 📸 *Screenshots coming soon — [help us add them!](https://github.com/your-org/heatwatch/issues)*

---

## 🛠️ Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology | Why |
|-------|-----------|-----|
| Language | Python 3.10+ | Universal in geospatial/climate science |
| Geo processing | `rasterio`, `geopandas` | Industry-standard, open-source |
| Satellite data | NASA Earthdata / USGS API | Free, global, well-documented |
| Visualization | `folium` (interactive maps) | Browser-ready, no frontend framework needed |
| API | FastAPI | Lightweight, auto-documented, async |
| Testing | `pytest` | Standard, beginner-friendly |
| CI/CD | GitHub Actions | Free for open source |

---

## 🚀 Quick Start

### Prerequisites

- Python 3.10+
- A free [NASA Earthdata account](https://urs.earthdata.nasa.gov/users/new) (for satellite data)
- Git

### Installation

```bash
# 1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/your-org/heatwatch.git
cd heatwatch

# 2. Create a virtual environment
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # Windows: venv\Scripts\activate

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -e ".[dev]"

# 4. Set up your NASA Earthdata credentials
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env and add your EARTHDATA_USERNAME and EARTHDATA_PASSWORD
```

### Run with Sample Data (no credentials needed)

```bash
# Analyze included sample data for Detroit, MI
heatwatch analyze --sample-city detroit

# Or run just the API server
uvicorn src.api.main:app --reload
# Visit http://localhost:8000/docs
```

### Full City Analysis

```bash
heatwatch analyze \
  --city "Phoenix, AZ" \
  --year 2022 \
  --output ./results \
  --export geojson,png,csv
```

